# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quantitative-finance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The **Black–Scholes** /ˌblæk ˈʃoʊlz/ or **Black–Scholes–Merton model** is a mathematical model for the dynamics of a financial market containing derivative investment instruments.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The equation and model are named after economists Fischer Black and Myron Scholes.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Merton, who first wrote an academic paper on the subject, is sometimes also credited.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The main principle behind the model is to hedge the option by buying and selling the underlying asset in a specific way to eliminate risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This type of hedging is called "continuously revised delta hedging" and is the basis of more complicated hedging strategies such as those used by investment banks and hedge funds.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The model is widely used, although often with some adjustments, by options market participants.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The model's assumptions have been relaxed and generalized in many directions, leading to a plethora of models that are currently used in derivative pricing and risk management.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The insights of the model, as exemplified by the Black–Scholes formula, are frequently used by market participants, as distinguished from the actual prices.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] These insights include no-arbitrage bounds and risk-neutral pricing (thanks to continuous revision).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Further, the Black–Scholes equation, a partial differential equation that governs the price of the option, enables pricing using numerical methods when an explicit formula is not possible.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Black–Scholes formula has only one parameter that cannot be directly observed in the market: the average future volatility of the underlying asset, though it can be found from the price of other options.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Since the option value (whether put or call) is increasing in this parameter, it can be inverted to produce a "volatility surface" that is then used to calibrate other models, e.g., for OTC derivatives.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Louis Bachelier's thesis in 1900 was the earliest publication to apply Brownian motion to derivative pricing, though his work had little impact for many years and included important limitations for its application to modern markets.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In the 1960's Case Sprenkle, James Boness, Paul Samuelson, and Samuelson's Ph.D. student at the time Robert C.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Merton all made important improvements to the theory of options pricing.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Fischer Black and Myron Scholes demonstrated in 1968 that a dynamic revision of a portfolio removes the expected return of the security, thus inventing the *risk neutral argument*.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] They based their thinking on work previously done by market researchers and practitioners including the work mentioned above, as well as work by Sheen Kassouf and Edward O.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Black and Scholes then attempted to apply the formula to the markets, but incurred financial losses, due to a lack of risk management in their trades.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In 1970, they decided to return to the academic environment.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] After three years of efforts, the formula—named in honor of them for making it public—was finally published in 1973 in an article titled "The Pricing of Options and Corporate Liabilities", in the *Journal of Political Economy*.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Merton was the first to publish a paper expanding the mathematical understanding of the options pricing model, and coined the term "Black–Scholes options pricing model".
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The formula led to a boom in options trading and provided mathematical legitimacy to the activities of options trading, led by Cboe Global Markets.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Merton and Scholes received the 1997 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences for their work, the committee citing their discovery of the risk neutral dynamic revision as a breakthrough that separates the option from the risk of the underlying security.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Although ineligible for the prize because of his death in 1995, Black was mentioned as a contributor by the Swedish Academy.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Black–Scholes model assumes that the market consists of at least one risky asset, usually called the stock, and one riskless asset, usually called the money market, cash, or bond.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] With these assumptions, suppose there is a derivative security also trading in this market.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] It is specified that this security will have a certain payoff on a specified future date, depending on the values of the stock up to that date.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Even though the path the stock price will take in the future is unknown, the derivative's price can be determined at the current time.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] For the special case of a European call or put option, Black and Scholes showed that "it is possible to create a hedged position, consisting of a long position in the stock and a short position in the option, whose value will not depend on the price of the stock".
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Their dynamic hedging strategy led to a partial differential equation which governs the price of the option.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Its solution is given by the Black–Scholes formula.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Several of these assumptions of the original model have been removed in subsequent extensions of the model.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Modern versions account for dynamic interest rates (Merton, 1976), transaction costs and taxes (Ingersoll, 1976), and dividend payout.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] of the option, also known as the exercise price.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] A key financial insight behind the equation is that one can perfectly hedge the option by buying and selling the underlying asset and the bank account asset (cash) in such a way as to "eliminate risk".
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This implies that there is a unique price for the option given by the Black–Scholes formula (see the next section).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Black–Scholes formula calculates the price of European put and call options.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This price is consistent with the Black–Scholes equation.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] It is possible to have intuitive interpretations of the Black–Scholes formula, with the main subtlety being the interpretation of $d_{\pm }$ and why there are two different terms.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The formula can be interpreted by first decomposing a call option into the difference of two binary options: an asset-or-nothing call minus a cash-or-nothing call (long an asset-or-nothing call, short a cash-or-nothing call).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] A call option exchanges cash for an asset at expiry, while an asset-or-nothing call just yields the asset (with no cash in exchange) and a cash-or-nothing call just yields cash (with no asset in exchange).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Black–Scholes formula is a difference of two terms, and these two terms are equal to the values of the binary call options.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] These binary options are less frequently traded than vanilla call options, but are easier to analyze.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] where $DN(d_{+})F$ is the present value of an asset-or-nothing call and $DN(d_{-})K$ is the present value of a cash-or-nothing call.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The *D* factor is for discounting, because the expiration date is in future, and removing it changes *present* value to *future* value (value at expiry).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Thus $N(d_{+})~F$ is the future value of an asset-or-nothing call and $N(d_{-})~K$ is the future value of a cash-or-nothing call.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In risk-neutral terms, these are the expected value of the asset and the expected value of the cash in the risk-neutral measure.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In fact, $d_{\pm }$ can be interpreted as measures of moneyness (in standard deviations) and $N(d_{\pm })$ as probabilities of expiring ITM (*percent moneyness*), in the respective numéraire, as discussed below.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] More precisely, the value of the asset at expiry is variable in terms of cash, but is constant in terms of the asset itself (a fixed quantity of the asset), and thus these quantities are independent if one changes numéraire to the asset rather than cash.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] If one uses spot *S* instead of forward *F,* in $d_{\pm }$ instead of the ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\sigma ^{2}}$ term there is ${\textstyle \left(r\pm {\frac {1}{2}}\sigma ^{2}\right)\tau ,}$ which can be interpreted as a drift factor (in the risk-neutral measure for appropriate numéraire).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In addition, another way to see that the naive interpretation is incorrect is that replacing $N(d_{+})$ by $N(d_{-})$ in the formula yields a negative value for out-of-the-money call options.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In detail, the terms $N(d_{+}),N(d_{-})$ are the *probabilities of the option expiring in-the-money* under the equivalent exponential martingale probability measure (numéraire=stock) and the equivalent martingale probability measure (numéraire=risk free asset), respectively.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] For related discussion – and graphical representation – see Datar–Mathews method for real option valuation.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The equivalent martingale probability measure is also called the risk-neutral probability measure.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Note that both of these are *probabilities* in a measure theoretic sense, and neither of these is the true probability of expiring in-the-money under the real probability measure.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] To calculate the probability under the real ("physical") probability measure, additional information is required—the drift term in the physical measure, or equivalently, the market price of risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] A standard derivation for solving the Black–Scholes PDE is given in the article Black–Scholes equation.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Feynman–Kac formula says that the solution to this type of PDE, when discounted appropriately, is actually a martingale.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Thus the option price is the expected value of the discounted payoff of the option.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Computing the option price via this expectation is the risk neutrality approach and can be done without knowledge of PDEs.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Note the expectation of the option payoff is not done under the real world probability measure, but an artificial risk-neutral measure, which differs from the real world measure.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] For the underlying logic see section "risk neutral valuation" under Rational pricing as well as section "Derivatives pricing: the Q world" under Mathematical finance; for details, once again, see Hull.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] "The Greeks" measure the sensitivity of the value of a derivative product or a financial portfolio to changes in parameter values while holding the other parameters fixed.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] They are partial derivatives of the price with respect to the parameter values.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] One Greek, "gamma" (as well as others not listed here) is a partial derivative of another Greek, "delta" in this case.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Greeks are important not only in the mathematical theory of finance, but also for those actively trading.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Financial institutions will typically set (risk) limit values for each of the Greeks that their traders must not exceed.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Delta is the most important Greek since this usually confers the largest risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Many traders will zero their delta at the end of the day if they are not speculating on the direction of the market and following a delta-neutral hedging approach as defined by Black–Scholes.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] When a trader seeks to establish an effective delta-hedge for a portfolio, the trader may also seek to neutralize the portfolio's gamma, as this will ensure that the hedge will be effective over a wider range of underlying price movements.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Greeks for Black–Scholes are given in closed form below.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] They can be obtained by differentiation of the Black–Scholes formula.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Note that the gamma and vega are the same value for calls and puts.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This can be seen directly from put–call parity, since the difference of a put and a call is a forward, which is linear in *S* and independent of *σ* (so a forward has zero gamma and zero vega).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In practice, some sensitivities are usually quoted in scaled-down terms, to match the scale of likely changes in the parameters.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] For example, rho is often reported divided by 10,000 (1 basis point rate change), vega by 100 (1 vol point change), and theta by 365 or 252 (1 day decay based on either calendar days or trading days per year).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Note that "Vega" is not a letter in the Greek alphabet; the name arises from misreading the Greek letter nu (variously rendered as $\nu$ , ν, and ν) as a V.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The above model can be extended for variable (but deterministic) rates and volatilities.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The model may also be used to value European options on instruments paying dividends.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In this case, closed-form solutions are available if the dividend is a known proportion of the stock price.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] American options and options on stocks paying a known cash dividend (in the short term, more realistic than a proportional dividend) are more difficult to value, and a choice of solution techniques is available (for example lattices and grids).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] For options on indices, it is reasonable to make the simplifying assumption that dividends are paid continuously, and that the dividend amount is proportional to the level of the index.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] for some constant q (the dividend yield).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] It is also possible to extend the Black–Scholes framework to options on instruments paying discrete proportional dividends.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This is useful when the option is struck on a single stock.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] A typical model is to assume that a proportion $\delta$ of the stock price is paid out at pre-determined times $t_{1},t_{2},\ldots ,t_{n}$ .
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] where $n(t)$ is the number of dividends that have been paid by time t .
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] is the forward price for the dividend paying stock.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The problem of finding the price of an American option is related to the optimal stopping problem of finding the time to execute the option.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] together with $V(S,t)\geq H(S)$ where $H(S)$ denotes the payoff at stock price S and the terminal condition: $V(S,T)=H(S)$ .
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In general this inequality does not have a closed form solution, though an American call with no dividends is equal to a European call and the Roll–Geske–Whaley method provides a solution for an American call with one dividend; see also Black's approximation.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Barone-Adesi and Whaley is a further approximation formula.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Here, the stochastic differential equation (which is valid for the value of any derivative) is split into two components: the European option value and the early exercise premium.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] With some assumptions, a quadratic equation that approximates the solution for the latter is then obtained.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This solution involves finding the critical value, $s*$ , such that one is indifferent between early exercise and holding to maturity.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Bjerksund and Stensland provide an approximation based on an exercise strategy corresponding to a trigger price.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The formula is readily modified for the valuation of a put option, using put–call parity.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This approximation is computationally inexpensive and the method is fast, with evidence indicating that the approximation may be more accurate in pricing long dated options than Barone-Adesi and Whaley.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Despite the lack of a general analytical solution for American put options, it is possible to derive such a formula for the case of a perpetual option – meaning that the option never expires (i.e., $T\rightarrow \infty$ ).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In this case, the time decay of the option is equal to zero, which leads to the Black–Scholes PDE becoming an ODE: ${1 \over {2}}\sigma ^{2}S^{2}{d^{2}V \over {dS^{2}}}+(r-q)S{dV \over {dS}}-rV=0$ Let $S_{-}$ denote the lower exercise boundary, below which it is optimal to exercise the option.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] By solving the Black–Scholes differential equation with the Heaviside function as a boundary condition, one ends up with the pricing of options that pay one unit above some predefined strike price and nothing below.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This pays out one unit of cash if the spot is above the strike at maturity.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This pays out one unit of cash if the spot is below the strike at maturity.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This pays out one unit of asset if the spot is above the strike at maturity.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This pays out one unit of asset if the spot is below the strike at maturity.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Denoting by *S* the FOR/DOM exchange rate (i.e., 1 unit of foreign currency is worth S units of domestic currency) one can observe that paying out 1 unit of the domestic currency if the spot at maturity is above or below the strike is exactly like a cash-or nothing call and put respectively.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Similarly, paying out 1 unit of the foreign currency if the spot at maturity is above or below the strike is exactly like an asset-or nothing call and put respectively.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In the standard Black–Scholes model, one can interpret the premium of the binary option in the risk-neutral world as the expected value = probability of being in-the-money * unit, discounted to the present value.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Black–Scholes model relies on symmetry of distribution and ignores the skewness of the distribution of the asset.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Market makers adjust for such skewness by, instead of using a single standard deviation for the underlying asset $\sigma$ across all strikes, incorporating a variable one $\sigma (K)$ where volatility depends on strike price, thus incorporating the volatility skew into account.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The skew matters because it affects the binary considerably more than the regular options.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] A binary call option is, at long expirations, similar to a tight call spread using two vanilla options.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] ${\frac {\partial C_{v}}{\partial \sigma }}$ is the Vega of the vanilla call; ${\frac {\partial \sigma }{\partial K}}$ is sometimes called the "skew slope" or just "skew".
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] If the skew is typically negative, the value of a binary call will be higher when taking skew into account.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Since a binary call is a mathematical derivative of a vanilla call with respect to strike, the price of a binary call has the same shape as the delta of a vanilla call, and the delta of a binary call has the same shape as the gamma of a vanilla call.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The assumptions of the Black–Scholes model are not all empirically valid.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The model is widely employed as a useful approximation to reality, but proper application requires understanding its limitations – blindly following the model exposes the user to unexpected risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In short, while in the Black–Scholes model one can perfectly hedge options by simply Delta hedging, in practice there are many other sources of risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Results using the Black–Scholes model differ from real world prices because of simplifying assumptions of the model.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] One significant limitation is that in reality security prices do not follow a strict stationary log-normal process, nor is the risk-free interest actually known (and is not constant over time).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The variance has been observed to be non-constant leading to models such as GARCH to model volatility changes.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Pricing discrepancies between empirical and the Black–Scholes model have long been observed in options that are far out-of-the-money, corresponding to extreme price changes; such events would be very rare if returns were lognormally distributed, but are observed much more often in practice.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The first point is self-evidently useful.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Useful approximation: although volatility is not constant, results from the model are often helpful in setting up hedges in the correct proportions to minimize risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Even when the results are not completely accurate, they serve as a first approximation to which adjustments can be made.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Basis for more refined models: The Black–Scholes model is *robust* in that it can be adjusted to deal with some of its failures.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Rather than considering some parameters (such as volatility or interest rates) as *constant,* one considers them as *variables,* and thus added sources of risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This is reflected in the Greeks (the change in option value for a change in these parameters, or equivalently the partial derivatives with respect to these variables), and hedging these Greeks mitigates the risk caused by the non-constant nature of these parameters.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Other defects cannot be mitigated by modifying the model, however, notably tail risk and liquidity risk, and these are instead managed outside the model, chiefly by minimizing these risks and by stress testing.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Explicit modeling: this feature means that, rather than *assuming* a volatility *a priori* and computing prices from it, one can use the model to solve for volatility, which gives the implied volatility of an option at given prices, durations and exercise prices.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Solving for volatility over a given set of durations and strike prices, one can construct an implied volatility surface.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In this application of the Black–Scholes model, a coordinate transformation from the *price domain* to the *volatility domain* is obtained.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Rather than quoting option prices in terms of dollars per unit (which are hard to compare across strikes, durations and coupon frequencies), option prices can thus be quoted in terms of implied volatility, which leads to trading of volatility in option markets.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] One of the attractive features of the Black–Scholes model is that the parameters in the model other than the volatility (the time to maturity, the strike, the risk-free interest rate, and the current underlying price) are unequivocally observable.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] All other things being equal, an option's theoretical value is a monotonic increasing function of implied volatility.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] By computing the implied volatility for traded options with different strikes and maturities, the Black–Scholes model can be tested.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] If the Black–Scholes model held, then the implied volatility for a particular stock would be the same for all strikes and maturities.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In practice, the volatility surface (the 3D graph of implied volatility against strike and maturity) is not flat.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The typical shape of the implied volatility curve for a given maturity depends on the underlying instrument.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Equities tend to have skewed curves: compared to at-the-money, implied volatility is substantially higher for low strikes, and slightly lower for high strikes.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Currencies tend to have more symmetrical curves, with implied volatility lowest at-the-money, and higher volatilities in both wings.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Commodities often have the reverse behavior to equities, with higher implied volatility for higher strikes.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Despite the existence of the volatility smile (and the violation of all the other assumptions of the Black–Scholes model), the Black–Scholes PDE and Black–Scholes formula are still used extensively in practice.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] A typical approach is to regard the volatility surface as a fact about the market, and use an implied volatility from it in a Black–Scholes valuation model.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This has been described as using "the wrong number in the wrong formula to get the right price".
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This approach also gives usable values for the hedge ratios (the Greeks).
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Even when more advanced models are used, traders prefer to think in terms of Black–Scholes implied volatility as it allows them to evaluate and compare options of different maturities, strikes, and so on.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] For a discussion as to the various alternative approaches developed here, see Financial economics § Challenges and criticism.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Black–Scholes cannot be applied directly to bond securities because of pull-to-par.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] As the bond reaches its maturity date, all of the prices involved with the bond become known, thereby decreasing its volatility, and the simple Black–Scholes model does not reflect this process.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] A large number of extensions to Black–Scholes, beginning with the Black model, have been used to deal with this phenomenon.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In practice, interest rates are not constant—they vary by tenor (coupon frequency), giving an interest rate curve which may be interpolated to pick an appropriate rate to use in the Black–Scholes formula.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Another consideration is that interest rates vary over time.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This volatility may make a significant contribution to the price, especially of long-dated options.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] This is simply like the interest rate and bond price relationship which is inversely related.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Taking a short stock position, as inherent in the derivation, is not typically free of cost; equivalently, it is possible to lend out a long stock position for a small fee.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In either case, this can be treated as a continuous dividend for the purposes of a Black–Scholes valuation, provided that there is no glaring asymmetry between the short stock borrowing cost and the long stock lending income.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Espen Gaarder Haug and Nassim Nicholas Taleb argue that the Black–Scholes model merely recasts existing widely used models in terms of practically impossible "dynamic hedging" rather than "risk", to make them more compatible with mainstream neoclassical economic theory.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] They also assert that Boness in 1964 had already published a formula that is "actually identical" to the Black–Scholes call option pricing equation.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Edward Thorp also claims to have guessed the Black–Scholes formula in 1967 but kept it to himself to make money for his investors.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] Emanuel Derman and Taleb have also criticized dynamic hedging and state that a number of researchers had put forth similar models prior to Black and Scholes.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In response, Paul Wilmott has defended the model.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In his 2008 letter to the shareholders of Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett wrote: "I believe the Black–Scholes formula, even though it is the standard for establishing the dollar liability for options, produces strange results when the long-term variety are being valued...
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Black–Scholes formula has approached the status of holy writ in finance ...
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] If the formula is applied to extended time periods, however, it can produce absurd results.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] In fairness, Black and Scholes almost certainly understood this point well.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] He said that the Black–Scholes equation was the "mathematical justification for the trading"—and therefore—"one ingredient in a rich stew of financial irresponsibility, political ineptitude, perverse incentives and lax regulation" that contributed to the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] He clarified that "the equation itself wasn't the real problem", but its abuse in the financial industry.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] The Black–Scholes model assumes positive underlying prices; if the underlying has a negative price, the model does not work directly.
[src:quantitative-finance/black-scholes-model] When dealing with options whose underlying can go negative, practitioners may use a different model such as the Bachelier model or simply add a constant offset to the prices.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Typically, then, financial modeling is understood to mean an exercise in either asset pricing or corporate finance of a quantitative nature.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] It involves translating a set of hypotheses about the behavior of markets or agents into numerical predictions.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] At the same time, "financial modeling" is a general term that means different things to different users; the reference usually relates either to accounting and corporate finance applications or to quantitative finance applications.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] In corporate finance and the accounting profession, *financial modeling* typically entails financial statement forecasting; usually the preparation of detailed company-specific models used for decision making purposes, valuation and financial analysis.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] In entrepreneurial and investment contexts, financial models are widely used to illustrate business viability and capital requirements for funding discussions.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Correspondingly, both characteristics are reflected (at least implicitly) in the mathematical form of these models: firstly, the models are in discrete time; secondly, they are deterministic.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] For discussion of the issues that may arise, see below; for discussion as to more sophisticated approaches sometimes employed, see Corporate finance § Quantifying uncertainty and Financial economics § Corporate finance theory.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Modelers are often designated "financial analyst" (and are sometimes referred to, tongue in cheek, as "number crunchers").
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Typically, the modeler will have completed an MBA or MSF with (optional) coursework in "financial modeling".
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Accounting qualifications and finance certifications such as the CIIA and CFA generally do not provide direct or explicit training in modeling.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] At the same time, numerous commercial training courses are offered, both through universities and privately.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] For the components and steps of business modeling here, see Outline of finance § Financial modeling; see also Valuation using discounted cash flows § Determine cash flow for each forecast period for further discussion and considerations.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Although purpose-built business software does exist, the vast proportion of the market is spreadsheet-based; this is largely since the models are almost always company-specific.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Also, analysts will each have their own criteria and methods for financial modeling.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Microsoft Excel now has by far the dominant position, having overtaken Lotus 1-2-3 in the 1990s.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Spreadsheet-based modelling can have its own problems, and several standardizations and "best practice"s have been proposed.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Here, professional guidelines emphasize transparent, auditable, and well-documented models.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Good practice includes separating input, calculation, and output sheets to enhance traceability and reduce error risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Practical training providers further highlight consistent formatting, clear labeling, and documentation of assumptions as essential for usability and stakeholder confidence.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] "Spreadsheet risk" is increasingly studied and managed; see model audit.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] One critique here, is that model *outputs*, i.e. line items, often inhere "unrealistic implicit assumptions" and "internal inconsistencies".
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] (For example, a forecast for growth in revenue but without corresponding increases in working capital, fixed assets and the associated financing, may imbed unrealistic assumptions about asset turnover, debt level and/or equity financing.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] See Sustainable growth rate § From a financial perspective.) What is required, but often lacking, is that all key elements are explicitly and consistently forecasted.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Related to this, is that modellers often additionally "fail to identify crucial assumptions" relating to *inputs*, "and to explore what can go wrong".
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] A further, more general critique relates to the lack of basic computer programming concepts amongst modelers, with the result that their models are often poorly structured, and difficult to maintain.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Serious criticism is also directed at the nature of budgeting, and its impact on the organization.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] In quantitative finance, *financial modeling* entails the development of a sophisticated mathematical model.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Models here deal with asset prices, market movements, portfolio returns and the like.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] The general nature of these problems is discussed under Mathematical finance § History: Q versus P, while specific techniques are listed under Outline of finance § Mathematical tools.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] For further discussion here see also: Brownian model of financial markets; Martingale pricing; Financial models with long-tailed distributions and volatility clustering; Extreme value theory; Historical simulation (finance).
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Modellers are generally referred to as "quants", i.e. quantitative analysts (or "rocket scientists") and typically have advanced (Ph.D. level) backgrounds in quantitative disciplines such as statistics, physics, engineering, computer science, mathematics or operations research.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Although spreadsheets are widely used here also (almost always requiring extensive VBA); custom C++, Fortran or Python, or numerical-analysis software such as MATLAB, are often preferred, particularly where stability or speed is a concern.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Additionally, for many (of the standard) derivative and portfolio applications, commercial software is available, and the choice as to whether the model is to be developed in-house, or whether existing products are to be deployed, will depend on the problem in question.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] See Quantitative analysis (finance) § Library quantitative analysis.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] The complexity of these models may result in incorrect pricing or hedging or both.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] This *Model risk* is the subject of ongoing research by finance academics, and is a topic of great, and growing, interest in the risk management arena.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Criticism of the discipline (often preceding the 2008 financial crisis by several years) emphasizes the differences between finance and the mathematical / physical sciences, and stresses the resultant caution to be applied by modelers, and by traders and risk managers using their models.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Notable here are Emanuel Derman and Paul Wilmott, authors of the *Financial Modelers' Manifesto*.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Some go further and question whether the mathematical- and statistical modeling techniques usually applied to finance are appropriate (see the assumptions made for options and for portfolios).
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] In fact, these may go so far as to question the "empirical and scientific validity... of modern financial theory".
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Notable here are Nassim Taleb and Benoit Mandelbrot.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] See also Mathematical finance § Criticism, Financial economics § Challenges and criticism and Financial engineering § Criticisms.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Several financial modeling competitions exist, emphasizing speed and accuracy in modeling.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] The Microsoft-sponsored ModelOff Financial Modeling World Championships were held annually from 2012 to 2019, with competitions throughout the year and a finals championship in New York or London.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] After its end in 2020, several other modeling championships have been started, including the Financial Modeling World Cup and Microsoft Excel Collegiate Challenge, also sponsored by Microsoft.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Philosophy of financial modeling is a branch of philosophy concerned with the foundations, methods, and implications of modeling science.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] In the philosophy of financial modeling, scholars have more recently begun to question the generally held assumption that financial modelers seek to represent any "real-world" or actually ongoing investment situation.
[src:quantitative-finance/financial-modeling] Instead, it has been suggested that the task of the financial modeler resides in demonstrating the possibility of a transaction in a prospective investment scenario, based on a limited set of possibility conditions initially assumed in the model.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] In general, there exist two separate branches of finance that require advanced quantitative techniques: derivatives pricing on the one hand, and risk and portfolio management on the other.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Mathematical finance overlaps heavily with the fields of computational finance and financial engineering.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The latter focuses on applications and modeling, often with the help of stochastic asset models, while the former focuses, in addition to analysis, on building tools of implementation for the models.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Also related is quantitative investing, which relies on statistical and numerical models (and lately machine learning) as opposed to traditional fundamental analysis when managing portfolios.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] French mathematician Louis Bachelier's doctoral thesis, defended in 1900, is considered the first scholarly work on mathematical finance.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] But mathematical finance emerged as a discipline in the 1970s, following the work of Fischer Black, Myron Scholes and Robert Merton on option pricing theory.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Mathematical investing originated from the research of mathematician Edward Thorp who used statistical methods to first invent card counting in blackjack and then applied its principles to modern systematic investing.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The subject has a close relationship with the discipline of financial economics, which is concerned with much of the underlying theory that is involved in financial mathematics.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] See: Valuation of options; Financial modeling; Asset pricing.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The fundamental theorem of arbitrage-free pricing is one of the key theorems in mathematical finance, while the Black–Scholes equation and formula are amongst the key results.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Today many universities offer degree and research programs in mathematical finance.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] There are two separate branches of finance that require advanced quantitative techniques: derivatives pricing, and risk and portfolio management.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] One of the main differences is that they use different probabilities such as the risk-neutral probability (or arbitrage-pricing probability), denoted by "Q", and the actual (or actuarial) probability, denoted by "P".
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The goal of derivatives pricing is to determine the fair price of a given security in terms of more liquid securities whose price is determined by the law of supply and demand.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The meaning of "fair" depends, of course, on whether one considers buying or selling the security.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Examples of securities being priced are plain vanilla and exotic options, convertible bonds, etc.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Once a fair price has been determined, the sell-side trader can make a market on the security.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Therefore, derivatives pricing is a complex "extrapolation" exercise to define the current market value of a security, which is then used by the sell-side community.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Quantitative derivatives pricing was initiated by Louis Bachelier in *The Theory of Speculation* ("Théorie de la spéculation", published 1900), with the introduction of the most basic and most influential of processes, Brownian motion, and its applications to the pricing of options.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Brownian motion is derived using the Langevin equation and the discrete random walk.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Bachelier modeled the time series of changes in the logarithm of stock prices as a random walk in which the short-term changes had a finite variance.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] This causes longer-term changes to follow a Gaussian distribution.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The theory remained dormant until Fischer Black and Myron Scholes, along with fundamental contributions by Robert C.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Merton, applied the second most influential process, the geometric Brownian motion, to option pricing.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Merton were awarded the 1997 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Black was ineligible for the prize because he died in 1995.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] A process satisfying (**1**) is called a "martingale".
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Thus the probability of the normalized security price process is called "risk-neutral" and is typically denoted by the blackboard font letter " $\mathbb {Q}$ ".
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The relationship (**1**) must hold for all times t: therefore the processes used for derivatives pricing are naturally set in continuous time.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Quantitative analysts (quants) in the "Q-world" focus on the pricing of derivative products.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Their role requires a detailed understanding of the mathematical models used for specific financial instruments.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Securities are priced individually, and thus the problems in the Q world are low-dimensional in nature.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Calibration is one of the main challenges of the Q world: once a continuous-time parametric process has been calibrated to a set of traded securities through a relationship such as (**1**), a similar relationship is used to define the price of new derivatives.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The main quantitative tools necessary to handle continuous-time Q-processes are Itô's stochastic calculus, simulation and partial differential equations (PDEs).
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Risk and portfolio management aims to model the statistically derived probability distribution of the market prices of all the securities at a given future investment horizon.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] This "real" probability distribution of the market prices is typically denoted by the blackboard font letter " $\mathbb {P}$ ", as opposed to the "risk-neutral" probability " $\mathbb {Q}$ " used in derivatives pricing.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Based on the P distribution, the buy-side community takes decisions on which securities to purchase in order to improve the prospective profit-and-loss profile of their positions considered as a portfolio.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Increasingly, elements of this process are automated; see Outline of finance § Quantitative investing for a listing of relevant articles.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] For their pioneering work, Markowitz and Sharpe, along with Merton Miller, shared the 1990 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, for the first time ever awarded for a work in finance.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The portfolio-selection work of Markowitz and Sharpe introduced mathematics to investment management.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] With time, the mathematics has become more sophisticated.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Thanks to Robert Merton and Paul Samuelson, one-period models were replaced by continuous time, Brownian-motion models, and the quadratic utility function implicit in mean–variance optimization was replaced by more general increasing, concave utility functions.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Furthermore, in recent years the focus shifted toward estimation risk, i.e., the dangers of incorrectly assuming that advanced time series analysis alone can provide completely accurate estimates of the market parameters.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] See Financial risk management § Investment management.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Much effort has gone into the study of financial markets and how prices vary with time.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Charles Dow, one of the founders of Dow Jones & Company and The Wall Street Journal, enunciated a set of ideas on the subject which are now called Dow Theory.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] This is the basis of the so-called technical analysis method of attempting to predict future changes.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] One of the tenets of "technical analysis" is that market trends give an indication of the future, at least in the short term.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The claims of the technical analysts are disputed by many academics.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] While numerous empirical studies have examined the effectiveness of technical analysis, there remains no definitive consensus on its usefulness in forecasting financial markets.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Over the years, increasingly sophisticated mathematical models and derivative pricing strategies have been developed, but their credibility was damaged by the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Contemporary practice of mathematical finance has been subjected to criticism from figures within the field notably by Paul Wilmott, and by Nassim Nicholas Taleb, in his book *The Black Swan*.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Taleb claims that the prices of financial assets cannot be characterized by the simple models currently in use, rendering much of current practice at best irrelevant, and, at worst, dangerously misleading.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Wilmott and Emanuel Derman published the *Financial Modelers' Manifesto* in January 2009 which addresses some of the most serious concerns.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Bodies such as the Institute for New Economic Thinking are now attempting to develop new theories and methods.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] In general, modeling the changes by distributions with finite variance is, increasingly, said to be inappropriate.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] In the 1960s it was discovered by Benoit Mandelbrot that changes in prices do not follow a Gaussian distribution, but are rather modeled better by Lévy alpha-stable distributions.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] The scale of change, or volatility, depends on the length of the time interval to a power a bit more than 1/2.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Large changes up or down are more likely than what one would calculate using a Gaussian distribution with an estimated standard deviation.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] But the problem is that it does not solve the problem as it makes parametrization much harder and risk control less reliable.
[src:quantitative-finance/mathematical-finance] Mathematical finance models do not, therefore, incorporate complex elements of human psychology that are critical to modeling modern macroeconomic movements such as the self-fulfilling panic that motivates bank runs.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Monte Carlo methods were first introduced to finance in 1964 by David B.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Hertz through his *Harvard Business Review* article, discussing their application in Corporate Finance.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In 1977, Phelim Boyle pioneered the use of simulation in derivative valuation in his seminal *Journal of Financial Economics* paper.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This article discusses typical financial problems in which Monte Carlo methods are used.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] It also touches on the use of so-called "quasi-random" methods such as the use of Sobol sequences.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] The Monte Carlo method encompasses any technique of statistical sampling employed to approximate solutions to quantitative problems.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Essentially, the Monte Carlo method solves a problem by directly simulating the underlying (physical) process and then calculating the (average) result of the process.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This very general approach is valid in areas such as physics, chemistry, computer science etc.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In finance, the Monte Carlo method is used to simulate the various sources of uncertainty that affect the value of the instrument, portfolio or investment in question, and to then calculate a representative value given these possible values of the underlying inputs.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] ("Covering all conceivable real world contingencies in proportion to their likelihood.") In terms of financial theory, this, essentially, is an application of risk neutral valuation; see also risk neutrality.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Although Monte Carlo methods provide flexibility, and can handle multiple sources of uncertainty, the use of these techniques is nevertheless not always appropriate.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In general, simulation methods are preferred to other valuation techniques only when there are several state variables (i.e. several sources of uncertainty).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] These techniques are also of limited use in valuing American style derivatives.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Many problems in mathematical finance entail the computation of a particular integral (for instance the problem of finding the arbitrage-free value of a particular derivative).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In many cases these integrals can be valued analytically, and in still more cases they can be valued using numerical integration, or computed using a partial differential equation (PDE).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] However, when the number of dimensions (or degrees of freedom) in the problem is large, PDEs and numerical integrals become intractable, and in these cases Monte Carlo methods often give better results.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] For more than three or four state variables, formulae such as Black–Scholes (i.e. analytic solutions) do not exist, while other numerical methods such as the Binomial options pricing model and finite difference methods face several difficulties and are not practical.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In these cases, Monte Carlo methods converge to the solution more quickly than numerical methods, require less memory and are easier to program.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] For simpler situations, however, simulation is not the better solution because it is very time-consuming and computationally intensive.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Monte Carlo methods can deal with derivatives which have path dependent payoffs in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] On the other hand, Finite Difference (PDE) solvers struggle with path dependence.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Monte-Carlo methods are harder to use with American options.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This is because, in contrast to a partial differential equation, the Monte Carlo method really only estimates the option value assuming a given starting point and time.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] However, for early exercise, we would also need to know the option value at the intermediate times between the simulation start time and the option expiry time.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In the Black–Scholes PDE approach these prices are easily obtained, because the simulation runs backwards from the expiry date.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In Monte-Carlo this information is harder to obtain, but it can be done for example using the least squares algorithm of Carriere (see link to original paper) which was made popular a few years later by Longstaff and Schwartz (see link to original paper).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] The fundamental theorem of arbitrage-free pricing states that the value of a derivative is equal to the discounted expected value of the derivative payoff where the expectation is taken under the risk-neutral measure [1].
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] An expectation is, in the language of pure mathematics, simply an integral with respect to the measure.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Monte Carlo methods are ideally suited to evaluating difficult integrals (see also Monte Carlo method).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Thus if we suppose that our risk-neutral probability space is $\mathbb {P}$ and that we have a derivative H that depends on a set of underlying instruments $S_{1},...,S_{n}$ .
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Then given a sample $\omega$ from the probability space the value of the derivative is $H(S_{1}(\omega ),S_{2}(\omega ),\dots ,S_{n}(\omega ))=:H(\omega )$ .
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Today's value of the derivative is found by taking the expectation over all possible samples and discounting at the risk-free rate.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] where ${DF}_{T}$ is the discount factor corresponding to the risk-free rate to the final maturity date *T* years into the future.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Now suppose the integral is hard to compute.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] We can approximate the integral by generating sample paths and then taking an average.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In finance, underlying random variables (such as an underlying stock price) are usually assumed to follow a path that is a function of a Brownian motion 2.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] To sample a path following this distribution from time 0 to T, we chop the time interval into M units of length $\delta t$ , and approximate the Brownian motion over the interval $dt$ by a single normal variable of mean 0 and variance $\delta t$ .
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Here each $\varepsilon _{i}$ is a draw from a standard normal distribution.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] We obtain the Monte-Carlo value of this derivative by generating *N* lots of *M* normal variables, creating *N* sample paths and so *N* values of *H*, and then taking the average.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Commonly the derivative will depend on two or more (possibly correlated) underlyings.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] The method here can be extended to generate sample paths of several variables, where the normal variables building up the sample paths are appropriately correlated.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] It follows from the central limit theorem that quadrupling the number of sample paths approximately halves the error in the simulated price (i.e. the error has order $\epsilon ={\mathcal {O}}\left(N^{-1/2}\right)$ convergence in the sense of standard deviation of the solution).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In practice Monte Carlo methods are used for European-style derivatives involving at least three variables (more direct methods involving numerical integration can usually be used for those problems with only one or two underlyings.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Estimates for the "Greeks" of an option i.e. the (mathematical) derivatives of option value with respect to input parameters, can be obtained by numerical differentiation.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This can be a time-consuming process (an entire Monte Carlo run must be performed for each "bump" or small change in input parameters).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Further, taking numerical derivatives tends to emphasize the error (or noise) in the Monte Carlo value – making it necessary to simulate with a large number of sample paths.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Practitioners regard these points as a key problem with using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Square root convergence is slow, and so using the naive approach described above requires using a very large number of sample paths (1 million, say, for a typical problem) in order to obtain an accurate result.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Remember that an estimator for the price of a derivative is a random variable, and in the framework of a risk-management activity, uncertainty on the price of a portfolio of derivatives and/or on its risks can lead to suboptimal risk-management decisions.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This state of affairs can be mitigated by variance reduction techniques.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] A simple technique is, for every sample path obtained, to take its antithetic path — that is given a path $\{\varepsilon _{1},\dots ,\varepsilon _{M}\}$ to also take $\{-\varepsilon _{1},\dots ,-\varepsilon _{M}\}$ .
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Since the variables $\varepsilon _{i}$ and $-\varepsilon _{i}$ form an antithetic pair, a large value of one is accompanied by a small value of the other.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This suggests that an unusually large or small output computed from the first path may be balanced by the value computed from the antithetic path, resulting in a reduction in variance.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Not only does this reduce the number of normal samples to be taken to generate *N* paths, but also, under same conditions, such as negative correlation between two estimates, reduces the variance of the sample paths, improving the accuracy.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] It is also natural to use a control variate.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Let us suppose that we wish to obtain the Monte Carlo value of a derivative *H*, but know the value analytically of a similar derivative I.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Then *H** = (Value of *H* according to Monte Carlo) + B*[(Value of *I* analytically) − (Value of *I* according to same Monte Carlo paths)] is a better estimate, where B is covar(H,I)/var(H).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] The intuition behind that technique, when applied to derivatives, is the following: note that the source of the variance of a derivative will be directly dependent on the risks (e.g. delta, vega) of this derivative.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This is because any error on, say, the estimator for the forward value of an underlier, will generate a corresponding error depending on the delta of the derivative with respect to this forward value.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] The simplest example to demonstrate this consists in comparing the error when pricing an at-the-money call and an at-the-money straddle (i.e. call+put), which has a much lower delta.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Therefore, a standard way of choosing the derivative *I* consists in choosing a replicating portfolios of options for *H*.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] In practice, one will price *H* without variance reduction, calculate deltas and vegas, and then use a combination of calls and puts that have the same deltas and vegas as control variate.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] The simulated payoffs are then not simply averaged as in the case of a simple Monte Carlo, but are first multiplied by the likelihood ratio between the modified probability distribution and the original one (which is obtained by analytical formulas specific for the probability distribution).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This will ensure that paths whose probability have been arbitrarily enhanced by the change of probability distribution are weighted with a low weight (this is how the variance gets reduced).
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This technique can be particularly useful when calculating risks on a derivative.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] When calculating the delta using a Monte Carlo method, the most straightforward way is the *black-box* technique consisting in doing a Monte Carlo on the original market data and another one on the changed market data, and calculate the risk by doing the difference.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Instead, the importance sampling method consists in doing a Monte Carlo in an arbitrary reference market data (ideally one in which the variance is as low as possible), and calculate the prices using the weight-changing technique described above.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] This results in a risk that will be much more stable than the one obtained through the *black-box* approach.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Instead of generating sample paths randomly, it is possible to systematically (and in fact completely deterministically, despite the "quasi-random" in the name) select points in a probability spaces so as to optimally "fill up" the space.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] The selection of points is a low-discrepancy sequence such as a Sobol sequence.
[src:quantitative-finance/monte-carlo-methods-in-finance] Taking averages of derivative payoffs at points in a low-discrepancy sequence is often more efficient than taking averages of payoffs at random points.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quants typically specialize in areas such as derivative structuring and pricing, risk management, portfolio management, and other finance-related activities.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The role is analogous to that of specialists in industrial mathematics working in non-financial industries.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative analysis often involves examining large datasets to identify patterns, such as correlations among liquid assets or price dynamics, including strategies based on trend following or mean reversion.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Applied quantitative analysis is commonly associated with quantitative investment management which includes a variety of methods such as statistical arbitrage, algorithmic trading, and electronic trading.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Some of the larger investment managers using quantitative analysis include Renaissance Technologies, Citadel Securities, D.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative finance started in 1900 with Louis Bachelier's doctoral thesis "Theory of Speculation", which provided a model to price options under a normal distribution.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Jules Regnault had posited already in 1863 that stock prices can be modelled as a random walk, suggesting "in a more literary form, the conceptual setting for the application of probability to stockmarket operations".
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] It was, however, only in the years 1960-1970 that the "merit of [these] was recognized" as options pricing theory was developed.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Harry Markowitz's 1952 doctoral thesis "Portfolio Selection" and its published version was one of the first efforts in economics journals to formally adapt mathematical concepts to finance (mathematics was until then confined to specialized economics journals).
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Markowitz formalized a notion of mean return and covariances for common stocks which allowed him to quantify the concept of "diversification" in a market.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] He showed how to compute the mean return and variance for a given portfolio and argued that investors should hold only those portfolios whose variance is minimal among all portfolios with a given mean return.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Thus, although the language of finance now involves Itô calculus, management of risk in a quantifiable manner underlies much of the modern theory.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Modern quantitative investment management was first introduced from the research of Edward Thorp, a mathematics professor at New Mexico State University (1961–1965) and University of California, Irvine (1965–1977).
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Considered the "Father of Quantitative Investing", Thorp sought to predict and simulate blackjack, a card-game he played in Las Vegas casinos.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] He was able to create a system, known broadly as card counting, which used probability theory and statistical analysis to successfully win blackjack games.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] His research was subsequently used during the 1980s and 1990s by investment management firms seeking to generate systematic and consistent returns in the U.S. stock market.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The field has grown to incorporate numerous approaches and techniques; see Outline of finance § Quantitative investing, Post-modern portfolio theory, Financial economics § Portfolio theory.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] In 1965, Paul Samuelson introduced stochastic calculus into the study of finance.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] In 1969, Robert Merton promoted continuous stochastic calculus and continuous-time processes.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Merton was motivated by the desire to understand how prices are set in financial markets, which is the classical economics question of "equilibrium", and in later papers he used the machinery of stochastic calculus to begin investigation of this issue.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] At the same time as Merton's work and with Merton's assistance, Fischer Black and Myron Scholes developed the Black–Scholes model, which was awarded the 1997 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] It provided a solution for a practical problem, that of finding a fair price for a European call option, i.e., the right to buy one share of a given stock at a specified price and time.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Such options are frequently purchased by investors as a risk-hedging device.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The various short-rate models (beginning with Vasicek in 1977), and the more general HJM Framework (1987), relatedly allowed for an extension to fixed income and interest rate derivatives.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Similarly, and in parallel, models were developed for various other underpinnings and applications, including credit derivatives, exotic derivatives, real options, and employee stock options.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quants are thus involved in pricing and hedging a wide range of securities – asset-backed, government, and corporate – additional to classic derivatives; see contingent claim analysis.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Emanuel Derman's 2004 book *My Life as a Quant* helped to both make the role of a quantitative analyst better known outside of finance, and to popularize the abbreviation "quant" for a quantitative analyst.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] In sales and trading, quantitative analysts work to determine prices, manage risk, and identify profitable opportunities.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Historically this was a distinct activity from trading but the boundary between a desk quantitative analyst and a quantitative trader is increasingly blurred, and it is now difficult to enter trading as a profession without at least some quantitative analysis education.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Front office work favours a higher speed to quality ratio, with a greater emphasis on solutions to specific problems than detailed modeling.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] FOQs typically are significantly better paid than those in back office, risk, and model validation.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Although highly skilled analysts, FOQs frequently lack software engineering experience or formal training, and bound by time constraints and business pressures, tactical solutions are often adopted.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Increasingly, quants are attached to specific desks.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Two cases are: XVA specialists, responsible for managing counterparty risk as well as (minimizing) the capital requirements under Basel III; and structurers, tasked with the design and manufacture of client specific solutions.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative analysis is used extensively by asset managers.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Some, such as FQ, AQR or Barclays, rely almost exclusively on quantitative strategies while others, such as PIMCO, BlackRock or Citadel use a mix of quantitative and fundamental methods.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] One of the first quantitative investment funds to launch was based in Santa Fe, New Mexico and began trading in 1991 under the name Prediction Company.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] By the late-1990s, Prediction Company began using statistical arbitrage to secure investment returns, along with three other funds at the time, Renaissance Technologies and D.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Prediction hired scientists and computer programmers from the neighboring Los Alamos National Laboratory to create sophisticated statistical models using "industrial-strength computers" in order to "[build] the Supercollider of Finance".
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Machine learning models are now capable of identifying complex patterns in financial market data.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] With the aid of artificial intelligence, investors are increasingly turning to deep learning techniques to forecast and analyze trends in stock and foreign exchange markets.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] See Applications of artificial intelligence § Trading and investment.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Major firms invest large sums in an attempt to produce standard methods of evaluating prices and risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] These differ from front office tools in that Excel is very rare, with most development being in C++, though Java, C# and Python are sometimes used in non-performance critical tasks.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] LQs spend more time modeling ensuring the analytics are both efficient and correct, though there is tension between LQs and FOQs on the validity of their results.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] LQs are required to understand techniques such as Monte Carlo methods and finite difference methods, as well as the nature of the products being modeled.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Often the highest paid form of Quant, ATQs make use of methods taken from signal processing, game theory, gambling Kelly criterion, market microstructure, econometrics, and time series analysis.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] This area has grown in importance in recent years, as the credit crisis exposed holes in the mechanisms used to ensure that positions were correctly hedged; see FRTB, Tail risk § Role of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Model validation (MV) takes the models and methods developed by front office, library, and modeling quantitative analysts and determines their validity and correctness; see model risk.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The MV group might well be seen as a superset of the quantitative operations in a financial institution, since it must deal with new and advanced models and trading techniques from across the firm.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Post crisis, regulators now typically talk directly to the quants in the middle office - such as the model validators - and since profits highly depend on the regulatory infrastructure, model validation has gained in weight and importance with respect to the quants in the front office.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Before the crisis however, the pay structure in all firms was such that MV groups struggle to attract and retain adequate staff, often with talented quantitative analysts leaving at the first opportunity.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] This gravely impacted corporate ability to manage model risk, or to ensure that the positions being held were correctly valued.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] An MV quantitative analyst would typically earn a fraction of quantitative analysts in other groups with similar length of experience.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] In the years following the crisis, as mentioned, this has changed.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative developers, sometimes called quantitative software engineers, or quantitative engineers, are computer specialists that assist, implement and maintain the quantitative models.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] They tend to be highly specialised language technicians that bridge the gap between software engineers and quantitative analysts.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The term is also sometimes used outside the finance industry to refer to those working at the intersection of software engineering and quantitative research.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The nonergodicity of financial markets and the time dependence of returns are central issues in modern approaches to quantitative trading.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Financial markets are complex systems in which traditional assumptions, such as independence and normal distribution of returns, are frequently challenged by empirical evidence.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Thus, under the non-ergodicity hypothesis, the future returns about an investment strategy, which operates on a non-stationary system, depend on the ability of the algorithm itself to predict the future evolutions to which the system is subject.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] As discussed by Ole Peters in 2011, ergodicity is a crucial element in understanding economic dynamics, especially in non-stationary contexts.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Identifying and developing methodologies to estimate this ability represents one of the main challenges of modern quantitative trading.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] In this perspective, it becomes fundamental to shift the focus from the result of individual financial operations to the individual evolutions of the system.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Operationally, this implies that clusters of trades oriented in the same direction offer little value in evaluating the strategy.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] On the contrary, sequences of trades with alternating buy and sell are much more significant.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Since they indicate that the strategy is actually predicting a statistically significant number of evolutions of the system.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Because of their backgrounds, quantitative analysts draw from various forms of mathematics: statistics and probability, calculus centered around partial differential equations, linear algebra, discrete mathematics, and econometrics.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Some on the buy side may use machine learning.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The majority of quantitative analysts have received little formal education in mainstream economics, and often apply a mindset drawn from the physical sciences.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quants use mathematical skills learned from diverse fields such as computer science, physics and engineering.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] These skills include (but are not limited to) advanced statistics, linear algebra and partial differential equations as well as solutions to these based upon numerical analysis.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] A typical problem for a mathematically oriented quantitative analyst would be to develop a model for pricing, hedging, and risk-managing a complex derivative product.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] These quantitative analysts tend to rely more on numerical analysis than statistics and econometrics.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] One of the principal mathematical tools of quantitative finance is stochastic calculus.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] A typical problem for a statistically oriented quantitative analyst would be to develop a model for deciding which stocks are relatively expensive and which stocks are relatively cheap.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] The model might include a company's book value to price ratio, its trailing earnings to price ratio, and other accounting factors.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] An investment manager might implement this analysis by buying the underpriced stocks, selling the overpriced stocks, or both.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Statistically oriented quantitative analysts tend to have more of a reliance on statistics and econometrics, and less of a reliance on sophisticated numerical techniques and object-oriented programming.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] These quantitative analysts tend to be of the psychology that enjoys trying to find the best approach to modeling data, and can accept that there is no "right answer" until time has passed and we can retrospectively see how the model performed.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Both types of quantitative analysts demand a strong knowledge of sophisticated mathematics and computer programming proficiency.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Quantitative analysis has traditionally been a major source of employment for those with PhD degrees in a quantitative discipline, and analysts often come from mathematics, applied mathematics, physics or engineering backgrounds, learning finance "on the job".
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] At the same time, the demand for quantitative skills has led to the creation of specialized Masters and PhD courses in financial engineering, mathematical finance and computational finance (as well as in specific topics such as financial reinsurance).
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] In particular, the Master of Quantitative Finance, Master of Financial Mathematics, Master of Computational Finance and Master of Financial Engineering are becoming popular with students and with employers.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] This has, in parallel, led to a resurgence in demand for actuarial qualifications, as well as commercial certifications such as the CQF.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Similarly, the more general Master of Finance (and Master of Financial Economics) increasingly includes a significant technical component.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] Likewise, masters programs in operations research, computational statistics, applied mathematics and industrial engineering may offer a quantitative finance specialization.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] While a quantitative analyst has typically needed extensive skills in computer programming — commonly C, C++ and Java, and lately R, MATLAB, Mathematica, and Python — data science and machine learning analysis and methods are increasingly employed.
[src:quantitative-finance/quantitative-analysis-finance] As such graduates of Master's in these areas are also hired as quants.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] Since the 1970s, the Wiener process has been widely applied in financial mathematics and economics to model the evolution in time of stock prices and bond interest rates.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] The main flavours of stochastic calculus are the Itô calculus and its variational relative the Malliavin calculus.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] For technical reasons the Itô integral is the most useful for general classes of processes, but the related Stratonovich integral is frequently useful in problem formulation (particularly in engineering disciplines).
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] The Stratonovich integral can readily be expressed in terms of the Itô integral, and vice versa.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] Stochastic integrals do NOT obey the usual chain rule.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] This enables problems to be expressed in a coordinate system invariant form, which is invaluable when developing stochastic calculus on manifolds other than **R***n*.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] The dominated convergence theorem does not hold for the Stratonovich integral; consequently it is very difficult to prove results without re-expressing the integrals in Itô form.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] The Itô integral is central to the study of stochastic calculus.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] The integral $\int H\,dX$ is defined for a semimartingale *X* and locally bounded **predictable** process *H*.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] where [*X*, *Y*]*t**c* denotes the optional quadratic covariation of the continuous parts of *X* and *Y*, which is the optional quadratic covariation minus the jumps of the processes X and Y , i.e.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] is also used to denote the Stratonovich integral.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] An important application of stochastic calculus is in mathematical finance, in which asset prices are often assumed to follow stochastic differential equations.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] For example, the Black–Scholes model prices options as if they follow a geometric Brownian motion, illustrating the opportunities and risks from applying stochastic calculus.
[src:quantitative-finance/stochastic-calculus] Besides the classical Itô and Fisk–Stratonovich integrals, many other notions of stochastic integrals exist, such as the Hitsuda–Skorokhod integral, the Marcus integral, and the Ogawa integral.
